text: DOI: 10.1002/cbic.200700140 Artificial Reconstruction of Two Cryptic Angucycline Antibiotic Biosynthetic Pathways Kaisa Palmu,[a] Keishi Ishida,[b] Pekka M(cid:19)nts(cid:19)l(cid:19),[a] Christian Hertweck,[b] and Mikko Mets(cid:19)-Ketel(cid:19)*[a, c] Genome-sequencing projects have revealed that Streptomyces bacteria have the genetic potential to produce considerably larger numbers of natural products than can be observed under standard laboratory conditions. Cryptic angucycline-type aromat- ic polyketide gene clusters are particularly abundant. Sequencing of two such clusters from Streptomyces sp. PGA64 and H021 re- vealed the presence of several open reading frames that could be involved in processing the basic angucyclic carbon skeleton. The pga gene cluster contains one putative FAD-dependant mono- Goxygenase (pgaE) and a putatively bifunctional monooxygenase/ short chain alcohol reductase (pgaM), whereas the cab cluster contains two similar monooxygenases (cabE and cabM) and an independent reductase (cabV). In this study we have reconstruct- ed the biosynthetic pathways for aglycone synthesis by cloning and sequentially expressing the angucycline tailoring genes with Actinomycetes are known as valuable producers of bioactive natural products, many of which have emerged as important clinical drugs.[1] Genome sequencing projects have revealed that these bacteria have the capacity to produce even more compounds than can be observed under standard laboratory conditions. Streptomyces coelicolor (A3)[2] and Streptomyces avermitilis[3] genomes, for instance, contain over 20 gene clus- ters for production of secondary metabolites, but only a limit- ed number could be assigned to known metabolites.[2–6] Such has been the impact of complete genome sequencing that several novel natural products have recently been isolated through the use of genomics as a guide to the microbial Gmetabolome.[7, 8]

A DNA fingerprinting study of type II polyketide biosynthesis genes from circa 100 Streptomyces strains has suggested that a large number of genes could be involved in the formation of angucyclines, a class of aromatic polyketides.[9] Up to 45 % of the aromatic antibiotic biosynthesis gene clusters detected in the study were classified as angucycline-type. This is in stark contrast to the discovery of angucyclines, since only 11 angu- cyclic compounds had been discovered by 1980, and even today they are relatively few in number.[10] The contradiction between the apparent genotypes and phenotypes suggests that many potentially interesting bioactive angucyclines are yet to be discovered. Indeed, recent molecular genetic studies have shown that the regulation of these types of gene clusters ChemBioChem 2007, 8, 1577 – 1584 C 2007 Wiley-VCH Verlag GmbH & Co. KGaA, Weinheim [b] Dr. K. Ishida, Prof. C. Hertweck genes required for the synthesis of the unmodified angucycline metabolite—UWM6—in Streptomyces lividans TK24. The expres- sion studies unequivocally showed that, after the production of UWM6, the pathways proceed through the action of the similar monooxygenases PgaE and CabE, followed by reactions catalysed by PgaM and CabMV. Analysis of the metabolites produced re- vealed that addition of pgaE and cabE genes directs both path- ways to a known shunt product, rabelomycin, whereas expres- sion of all genes from a given pathway results in the production of the novel angucycline metabolites gaudimycin A and B. How- ever, one of the end products is most probably further modified by endogenous S. lividans TK24 enzymes. These experiments demonstrate that genes that are either inactive or cryptic in their native host can be used as biosynthetic tools to generate new compounds.

PGA64.[14] The biosynthesis of many angucyclines has been character- ised in detail and follows a pathway typical of aromatic poly- ketides. Biosynthesis begins with the iterative action of a mini- mal PKS complex consisting of a ketoacylsynthase/chain length factor heterodimer (KSa/KSb, or KS/CLF) and an acyl carrier pro- tein (ACP), which formally assembles a polyketide chain from ten acetate building blocks. Structures and numbering of angucycline metabolites UWM6 (1), rabelomycin (2), gaudimycin A (3), gaudimycin B (4) and WP 3688-2 (5). the pathways diverge through the action of numerous tailor- ing or so-called post-PKS enzymes. In this context, oxygenases (OXY) play a key role in generating metabolic diversity.[20] The most common post-PKS gene products found in angucycline gene clusters are similar to proteins from two well known enzyme families: FAD-dependent oxygenases and short chain alcohol dehydrogenase/reductases (SDRs).[21–23] Studying reac- tions catalysed by these post-PKS enzymes has been shown to be a challenging task, as most modifications of 1 lead to vari- ous possible rearrangements of the polyaromatic carbon skele- ton and/or to shunt products.[24, 25] We have recently detected, cloned and sequenced two cryp- tic angucycline-type gene clusters by using hybridisation probes generated with the DNA fingerprinting method.[9, 14, 26] Characterisation of such orphan gene loci opens up the possi- bility to study the regulatory mechanisms underlying the sup- pression of gene expression and to give access to new biosyn- thetic genes for combinatorial biosynthesis purposes. In this study we aimed at understanding the functions and the bio- synthetic order of post-PKS reactions in these two pathways by heterologous expression of different combinations of agly- cone biosynthesis genes in S. lividans TK24. According to sequence analysis, the pga cluster contains two putative post-PKS genes (black in Figure 1) that encode a putative FAD-dependent oxygenase PgaE and a two-domain protein PgaM, which contains a monooxygenase domain con- nected to a domain homologous to SDRs. The cab cluster, in turn, harbours three modification genes, which encode two monooxygenases—CabE and CabM—and an independent SDR gene product CabV. The main difference between the two sys- tems is that on the pga pathway the equivalents of cabM and cabV have fused together to form a single putatively bifunc- tional gene: pgaM. Analysis of FAD monooxygenases that utilise aromatic poly- ketides as substrates

Flavin-dependent monooxygenases have been studied for sev- eral decades, and their mechanism of action is well de- fined.[27, 28] The enzymes use molecular oxygen, which they acti- vate through the action of flavin adenine dinucleotide (FAD), and attach a single oxygen atom to the substrate. NAD(P)H is consumed during the reaction in order to re-establish the lost redox potential of FAD.[28] To gain insight into the sequence– function relationships of the deduced pga and cab gene prod- ucts, phylogenetic analyses were performed with known FAD- dependent oxygenases from other antibiotic biosynthesis pathways. Protein sequences were aligned by pairwise align- ment by using the BLOSUM62 matrix, and the phylogenetic tree shown in Figure 2 was constructed by the Neighbor-Join- ing method, by use of 100 rounds in bootstrap analysis.[29] En- zymes found from angucycline pathways formed two distinct clades, which comprised: a) enzymes that have been suggest- ChemBioChem 2007, 8, 1577 – 1584 Heterologous Expression of Angucycline Post-PKS Genes Figure 2. Phylogenetic tree of selected flavin-dependent monooxygenases involved in aromatic polyketide syn- Gthesis. The tree was constructed by the Neighbor-Joining method and bootstrap values for the main clades are shown. Scale bar represents 10 % dissimilarity. ed to catalyse the formation of the quinone moiety—that is, oxidation at position 12—and b) enzymes catalysing reactions at other positions. Except for the latter group, the phylogenet- ic tree correlated well with the various functions of the en- zymes: for instance, anthracycline 11-hydroxylases, tetraceno- mycin 4,4 a,12 b-trihydroxylases, tetracycline 6-hydroxylases, and even putative spiroketal Baeyer–Villiger oxygenases were grouped together. To establish the functions of the putative oxygenase genes pgaE and pgaM experimentally, they were cloned both individually and together into a previously constructed gene cassette, con- taining all of the genes (Table 1) required for the synthesis of the first stable angucyclic metabo- lite, compound 1.[18] Firstly, pgaE and pgaM were PCR amplified by use of oligonucleotides con- taining additional recognition sequences for unique restriction sites to facilitate cloning steps. The PCR products were then cloned and sequenced individu- ally prior to further cloning steps into final expression plas- mids as described in the Experi- mental Section. The genes were cloned in a single operon struc- ture under the control of the strong consecutive promoter ermEp in the high copy number Streptomyces plasmid pIJE486.[30] Expression of the basic angu- cycline PKS genes in the absence of post-PKS modification genes results in the production of two metabolites: 1 and ra- belomycin (2; Scheme 1). Several studies have suggested that 2 is formed through nonenzymatic conversion of 1 by oxida- tion and dehydration.[18, 24, 25] For instance, use of an absorbent such as XAD-7 in the cultivations, which conceivably protects the metabolites from oxidation, greatly enhances the produc- tion of 1.[18] In the coexpression experiment, addition of pgaE Expression of post-PKS genes from the pga cluster in Strep- tomyces lividans TK24 UWM6 rabelomycin UWM6 gaudimycin A UWM6 UWM6 UWM6 rabelomycin gaudimycin B [18] this work this work this work this work this work this work [26] this work

to the gene cassette shifted production drastically towards 2, and no traces of 1 could be detected even from culture broths with added absorbent (see the Supporting Information for HPLC chromatograms). In contrast, addition of pgaM alone did not have any effect on the production profile, as 1 remained the main product. Cloning of both modification genes, pgaE and pgaM, into the gene cassette resulted in the production of a novel metabolite, as shown by HPLC/UV/Vis monitoring. The compound was named gaudimycin A (3, Scheme 1), since Streptomyces sp. PGA64 had been isolated from a soil sample collected from Parc GNell in Barcelona, designed by the archi- tect Antoni GaudO. The 1H and 13C NMR spectra of the purified product indicated that 3 has a typical angucycline structure based on the benz[a]anthracene skeleton. In particular, three ketone carbonyl carbons—C-1 (d = 197.7), C-7 (d = 189.4) and C-12 (d = 182.1)—and the ABX spin resonances—H-9 (d = 7.24 d), H-10 (d = 7.66 t) and H-11 (d = 7.39 d)—strongly suggested the angucycline moiety of 3 (Table 2). More detailed analysis revealed that the by COSY, HMQC and HMBC (Scheme 2) Gstructure of 3 is very similar to that of WP 3688-2 (5; Scheme 1),[31, 32] except for positions C-2 (dC = 122.5 ppm in 3, dC = 50.9 ppm in 5) and C-3 (dC = 155.2 ppm in 3, dC = 72.6 ppm in 5). In addition, MS data showed a molecular ion peak (m/z = 340) in 3 that is 18 amu lower than that of 5. These results showed 3 to be 3-dehydroxy-5.

Expression of post-PKS genes from the cab cluster in GStreptomyces lividans TK24 In analogy to the approach described above, the cabM and cabV genes were amplified by PCR, sequenced and cloned, and coexpressed individually and together (Table 1). Investiga- tion of the metabolic profiles of the transformants showed that CabM and CabV do not use 1 as substrate, since it re- mained the main product of all of these recombinant strains. The cabE gene was included together with early biosynthesis genes from the cab gene cluster on a PstI fragment, which was cloned into plasmid pIJE486, to result in strain S. lividans TK24/ pS11P2 that produces 2 as its main product.[26] In this study, a larger BglII fragment containing the early biosynthesis genes with the cabM and cabV genes was cloned into vector pIJ487, 124.0 136.7 118.7 131.5 182.1 142.8 74.5 23.2 ChemBioChem 2007, 8, 1577 – 1584 196.7 121.6 160.1[d] 36.2 145.1 188.2 114.4 160.1[d] 124.2 136.8 119.0 131.9 185.7 140.3 79.4 23.6 124.4 136.8 119.4 132.1 186.6 140.2 80.0 24.2 Heterologous Expression of Angucycline Post-PKS Genes

resulting in plasmid pS11B2 (Table 1). Cultivation of this strain resulted in the production of a new metabolite: gaudimycin B (4; Scheme 1), which was confirmed to be a novel angucycline metabolite by MS and NMR analysis (Table 2). MS data showed a molecular ion peak (m/z 356) that was 16 amu higher than that of 3. The 1H and 13C NMR spectra were highly similar to those of 3, with major differences only seen at position 6. The COSY, HMQC and HMBC correlations revealed that 4 is 6-hy- (d = droxy-3 (Scheme 2), but overlapping carbon signals 160.1 ppm) at C-3 and C-8 in [D6]DMSO interrupted the eluci- dation of the structure in rings A and D. In [D6]DMSO/CD2Cl2 (30:70), however, the carbon signals at C-3 and C-8 were well separated at 161.8 and 160.8 ppm, respectively. Two broad hy- droxy protons at positions 4 a (d = 5.19 ppm) and 12 b (d = 6.38 ppm) were also observed as singlet signals in this solvent system. The relative stereochemistry at position 6 was verified by 1D NOE experiments in [D6]DMSO/CD2Cl2 (30:70), in which NOEs were observed between H-6 and the hydroxy protons at carbons 4 a and 12 b.

Genome sequencing projects have revealed that many organ- isms, most notably Streptomyces,[2, 3] but also other bacteria,[33] fungi[34, 35] and plants,[36] have the genetic capacity to produce a far greater number of secondary metabolites than have been observed through traditional cultivation methods. Recently, several studies have used these data in genome mining assist- ed natural product discovery, as exemplified by the isolation of coelichelin,[5] germicidins,[6] halstoctacosanolides[37] and ECO- 02 301[38] from Streptomyces. These approaches, however, rely on the presumption that the identified gene clusters are active in the producing strain and that the production level is suffi- cient for isolation of metabolites. Therefore, new strategies for their activation are urgently needed to make full use of this largely untapped reservoir of potential bioactive compounds. In this study we have taken the next logical step and have uti- lised cryptic genes out of their native environments in order to harness the full genetic potential of Streptomyces for expansion of natural product diversity. The aim of this study was partial characterisation of two cryptic angucycline-type biosynthesis pathways through sequential expression of post-PKS genes with the focus on putative FAD-dependent oxygenases. The re- combination experiments resulted in the production of two novel angucycline metabolites—3 and 4—in S. lividans TK24, which strongly supports the hypothesis that genes that are either inactive or cryptic in their native host can be used as biosynthetic tools to generate new compounds. Neither 3 or 4 could be detected from cultures of the native hosts, Streptomy- ces sp. PGA64 and H021, respectively. The heterologous expression experiments also give insight into the order of the polyketide tailoring reactions, as well as clarifying the functions of the gene products. FAD-dependent monooxygenases are divided into two subgroups according to their mechanism of action: the oxygen atom can either be Gattached to an aromatic ring in a hydroxylation reaction[28] as in the cases of the well characterised phenol hydroxylase[39] ChemBioChem 2007, 8, 1577 – 1584

C 2007 Wiley-VCH Verlag GmbH & Co. KGaA, Weinheim and p-hydroxybenzoate hydroxylase,[40] while in the so-called Baeyer–Villiger monooxygenase group the reaction leads to an oxygen insertion reaction[28] as in the case of cyclohexane monooxygenase.[41] This latter group also contains enzymes in which the reaction leads to oxidative C(cid:1)C bond cleavage, as in jadomycin[24] and mithramycin[42] biosynthesis. The results show that in both biosynthesis pathways the similar pgaE and cabE gene products catalyse the first reaction, leading to the production of the known shunt product 2. This is in agreement with findings from the landomycin pathway,[23] but in contrast to the proposed order of reactions in the urdamycin path- way.[25] All data lead to the conclusion that PgaE and CabE Gcatalyse aromatic hydroxylation at position 12, using 1 as a Gsubstrate (Scheme 3).

The biosynthesis continues with the action of the pgaM and cabMV gene products. Structural elucidation of 3 and 4 reveals that both compounds have gone through 2,3-dehydration as well as hydroxylation at position 12 b (Scheme 3). Therefore it is likely that CabV and the reductase domain of PgaM catalyse 2,3-dehydration in a manner similar to that seen in landomycin biosynthesis, where it has been suggested that aromatisation of the A-ring occurs through the action of a homologous re- ductase lanV.[21] According to sequence analyses the angucy- cline reductases are most closely related to SDR dehydrogenas- es.[43, 44] However, the so called “extended SDR superfamily” does contain members that use the same conserved tyrosine residue in the active site for dehydration reactions,[43, 45] which gives support to the 2,3-dehydration function assigned here. CabM and the oxygenase domain of PgaM, on the other hand, probably catalyse Baeyer–Villiger-type monooxygenation at position 12 b, as in the urdamycin biosynthetic pathway.[25] A surprising finding is the lack of a hydroxy group at posi- tion 6 of 3. This is most probably the result of action of endog- enous S. lividans TK24 enzymes, since the loss of the 6-hydroxy group would require two reactions, dehydration and enoyl Greduction, not typically catalysed by enzymes homologous to PgaE or PgaM. The only difference between 3 and 4 is, in effect, in the 6-hydroxy group, which raises interesting ques- tions as to why the group is retained in 4, since the host strain used was the same. A likely explanation is a difference in abso- lute stereochemistry in one or more of the hydroxy groups at positions 6, 4 a or 12 b, resulting in a situation in which only the 6-hydroxy intermediate of 3 is an acceptable substrate for the endogenous enzymes.

Phylogenetic analysis suggests that the two angucycline monooxygenase groups have arisen through gene duplication and gain-of-function after the formation of the angucycline Glineage (Figure 2). The logical conclusion would be that the Gancestral function is oxidation at position 12 and subsequent quinone formation, which is a common event in angucycline pathways. The other group contains gene products that per- form more varied tailoring reactions with favoured oxygena- tion positions at 12 b, as in the urdamycin[25] and the cryptic cab and pga pathways, or at position 6, as in landomycin bio- synthesis.[23] This group also contains JadF from the jadomycin pathway, which has recently been shown to be involved in B- ring cleavage.[22] Interestingly, in this last group there appears Scheme 3. Putative biosynthetic pathway of gaudimycins produced in this study. Structures within brackets indicate hypothetical intermediates. to be no correlation between the evolutionary path and the function of the enzymes, unlike in all other branches of the tree. This surprising result can possibly be attributed to the highly reactive nature of the polyaromatic substrates. The posi- tion of oxygenation might change with only few changes in the protein sequence, as precise alignment of the substrate in the active site might not be exceedingly critical for enzyme ac- tivity. Recently, enzymes that employ such “substrate-assisted” catalysis have been characterised from other aromatic poly- Gketide biosynthesis pathways.[17, 46, 47] Moreover, unusual bifunc- tionality has been observed with enzymes that catalyse angu- cycline post-PKS reactions,[21, 22] supporting the high inherent reactivity of the substrates. Finally, the lack of sequence-to- function correlation with angucycline monooxygenases indi- cates that their function cannot be deduced in silico and sug- gests that gene products from the other unknown clusters (AlpF and Aur1I) might encode novel activities. These, howev- er, can only be confirmed by further in vivo studies.

Bacterial strains and culture conditions: For isolation of plasmid DNA and generation of template DNA for PCR reactions, Strepto- myces strains were grown in TSB medium (Oxoid, England), supple- mented with appropriate antibiotics. S. lividans TK24 was grown in YEME[48] for generation of protoplasts. E1[49] was used for produc- C 2007 Wiley-VCH Verlag GmbH & Co. KGaA, Weinheim tion of metabolites both with and without added XAD-7 (20 g L) absorbent. Streptomyces cultures were grown in shaking flasks (330 rpm) at 28 8C for 3–7 days. E. coli TOP10 (Invitrogen, USA) was used as a routine cloning host, and it was grown in LB[50] supple- mented with ampicillin (100 mg mL(cid:1)1). General DNA procedures and transformations: The genes pgaE, pgaM, cabM and cabV were amplified from chromosomal DNA templates by PCR with use of oligonucleotides with added unique restriction sites to facilitate cloning steps. The unique sites added upstream and downstream of the genes were NsiI and AvrII (pgaE), SnaBI and HindIII (pgaM), AvrII and NheI (cabM) and NsiI and AvrII (cabV). The genes were amplified with Dynazyme II (Finnzymes, Finland), cloned with the TOPO-TA -cloning system (Invitrogen, USA) and sequenced with an ABI Prism 310 sequencer (Applied Biosystems, USA) with use of universal primers. E. coli cells were transformed by electroporation,[50] while protoplast transformation was used to introduce expression plasmids into S. lividans TK24.[48]

Construction of expression plasmids: The plasmids resulting from TOPO-TA cloning of PCR products were annotated in the form of pTOPO plus gene name. From these constructs, the genes pgaE and cabM were added as blunt-ended EcoRI fragments to the EcoRV site of plasmid pEMC6BD,[18] giving plasmids pEJ1 and pEJ3, respectively. The gene cabV was added to the same EcoRV site as a blunt-ended EcoRI–HindIII fragment, resulting in plasmid pEJ8. The gene pgaM was added as an AvrII–NsiI fragment to a similarly cut pEJ1, resulting in replacement of pgaE with pgaM in plasmid pEJ6. The gene pgaM was also added as a blunt-ended EcoRV–AvrII frag- ment to the AvrII site of pEJ1, resulting in plasmid pEJ7, which ChemBioChem 2007, 8, 1577 – 1584 Heterologous Expression of Angucycline Post-PKS Genes

thus contains both post-PKS genes from the pga pathway. The gene cabM was added as an AvrII–HindIII fragment to a similarly cut pEJ1, resulting in pEJ5. The gene cabV was added as a blunt- ended EcoRI–HindIII fragment to a blunt-ended AvrII site of plasmid pEJ3, giving plasmid pEJ4, which contains the post-PKS genes cabM and cabV. The biosynthesis genes from all of these constructs were then ligated as XbaI–HindIII fragments to similarly cut Strepto- myces expression vector pIJE486[30] before transformation. The Gdesignation of the expression plasmids was changed from the pEJ abbreviation to pSJ upon cloning into Streptomyces. For unknown reasons, the plasmid pEJ1 could not be cloned into Streptomyces, and therefore the pgaE expression plasmid was constructed by cut- ting out cabM as an AvrII–HindIII fragment from pSJ5, resulting in plasmid pSJ1e. The expression plasmid pS11B2 was constructed by cloning a BglII fragment from the PKS region of the cab cluster to a BamHI site of vector pI J487[48] in S. lividans TK24.

Phylogenetic analysis: Genes from aromatic biosynthesis path- ways homologous to FAD-dependent monooxygenases were downloaded from GenBank and analysed with the program Clus- talW.[29] The well characterised phenol hydroxylase[39] and 3-hydrox- ybenzoate hydroxylase[40] were added to the multiple alignment to check the alignment of residues known to be important for FAD binding. No manual adjustments of the alignment had to be made. For the bifunctional enzymes, the adjoining linker and the reductase domain were left out, generating truncated genes pgaMox, urdMox, aur1Iox and lanM2ox. Analysis of metabolites: From cultivations without XAD-7, sam- ples (300 mL) were extracted with methanol/chloroform (1:1, (300 mL, 1 m 400 mL) under acidic (300 mL, 1 m HCl) or neutral sodium phosphate, pH 7.0) conditions. The organic solvent was evaporated and solubilised in methanol or chloroform for HPLC and TLC analysis, respectively. From cultivations with XAD-7, the resin was separated from the culture broth by repeated decanting, and the compounds were ex- tracted with methanol for further analysis. HPLC samples were ana- lysed with a Shimadzu SCL-10Avp (Shimadzu, Japan) and a Merck LiChroCART 250–4 RP-18 (5 mm) column with a 40 or 45 min gradi- ent from 15 % to 95 % acetonitrile in 0.1 % formic acid. TLC samples were run with CHCl3/MeOH (95:5) mobile phase. Purification of gaudimycins A and B: For production of metabo- lites, strains S. lividans TK24/pSJ7 and S. lividans TK24/pS11B2 were grown in E1 + XAD media (5 L) in 250 mL and 500 mL flasks. compounds were extracted from XAD with isopropanol/water mix- tures (1:1). Gaudimycin A was subjected to repeated silica gel chro- matography with use of a chloroform/methanol gradient. Gaudi- mycin B was extracted with dichloromethane and precipitated from methanol and further from hexane. As a final step, gaudimy- cins A and B were purified by preparative HPLC with a Merck Hita- chi l-6200 A, a Merck LiChroCART 250–10 RP-18 (10 mm) column and a water/acetonitrile gradient. Calculation of gaudimycin yields was not possible due to degradation of an unknown amount (30– 70 %) of both compounds under acidic conditions during purifica- tion.
